.sp
The \fBgc\-interval\fR doesn\(cqt affect element timeout, but it does affect memory reclaim\&. A large set that rarely has elements that time out can use a higher (less frequent) garbage collection to save cpu time, whereas sets that see many updates with short\-lived elements will benefit from a lower interval\&. Lower intervals ensure the set stays below its maximum size\&. Internally, a timed\-out entry stays around until it is removed by the garbage collector, which also decrements the sets element count\&. This also means that it is possible to have a set that can not accept more elements, even if all elements timed out, if the \fBgc\-interval\fR is set too large\&.
.sp
The \fBsize\fR defines the upper limit of the amount of elements that the set can support\&. Mandatory for sets that are added to from the ruleset with the \fBadd\fR and \fBupdate\fR keywords\&. Providing the \fBsize\fR keyword for sets that are only added to via \fBnft add element\fR allows for a more compact (memory conserving) set implementation selection, but it is not required\&.
.sp
The optional \fBpolicy\fR keyword can be used to request a more memory\-conserving set implementation\&.
.sp
\fBauto\-merge\fR instructs the nftables frontend to merge adjacent and overlapping ranges\&. Example: When the set contains range \fB1\&.2\&.3\&.1\-1\&.2\&.3\&.4\fR, then adding element \fB1\&.2\&.3\&.2\fR has no effect\&. Adding \fB1\&.2\&.3\&.5\fR changes the existing range to cover \fB1\&.2\&.3\&.1\-1\&.2\&.3\&.5\fR\&. Without this flag, \fB1\&.2\&.3\&.2\fR can not be added and \fB1\&.2\&.3\&.5\fR is inserted as a new entry\&.
