.\}
.nf
\fBfib\fR \fIFIB_TUPLE\fR \fIFIB_RESULT\fR
\fIFIB_TUPLE\fR := { \fBsaddr\fR | \fBdaddr\fR} [ \fB\&.\fR { \fBiif\fR | \fBoif\fR } \fB\&.\fR \fBmark\fR ]
\fIFIB_RESULT\fR  := { \fBoif\fR | \fBoifname\fR | \fBcheck\fR | \fBtype\fR }
.fi
.if n \{\
.RE
.\}
.sp
A fib expression queries the fib (forwarding information base) to obtain information such as the output interface index\&.
.sp
The first arguments to the \fBfib\fR expression are the input keys to be passed to the fib lookup function\&. One of \fBsaddr\fR or \fBdaddr\fR is mandatory, they are also mutually exclusive\&.
.sp
\fBmark\fR, \fBiif\fR and \fBoif\fR keywords are optional modifiers to influence the search result, see the \fBFIB_TUPLE\fR keyword table below for a description\&. The \fBiif\fR and \fBoif\fR tuple keywords are also mutually exclusive\&.
.sp
The last argument to the \fBfib\fR expression is the desired result type\&.
.sp
\fBoif\fR asks to obtain the interface index that would be used to send packets to the packets source (\fBsaddr\fR key) or destination (\fBdaddr\fR key)\&. If no routing entry is found, the returned interface index is 0\&.
.sp
\fBoifname\fR is like \fBoif\fR, but it fills the interface name instead\&. This is useful to check dynamic interfaces such as ppp devices\&. If no entry is found, an empty interface name is returned\&.
.sp
\fBtype\fR returns the address type such as unicast or multicast\&. A complete list of supported address types can be shown with \fBnft\fR \fBdescribe\fR \fBfib_addrtype\fR\&.
